Recall that the differential equation is given by

\begin{align*}
\frac{dS}{dt} = 1.9 - \frac1{20}S
\end{align*}

We use separation of variables and bring all terms with \emph{S} to the
left hand side, and all terms involving \emph{t} to the right hand side.
So we multiply both sides with $\displaystyle dt$ and divide by
$\displaystyle 1.9 - \frac1{20}S$:

\begin{align*}
\frac{dS}{1.9 - \frac1{20}S} = dt
\end{align*}

Let's now integrate both sides:

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{dS}{1.9 - \frac1{20}S} = \int dt
\end{align*}

The integral on the right hand side is simply $\displaystyle t+C_1.$ To
solve the left hand side, use the substitution
$u = 1.9 - \frac{1}{20}S,\ dS=-20\,du$ and obtain

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{dS}{1.9 - \frac1{20}S} = \int \frac{-20\,du}{u} = -20 \ln|u| = -20 \ln\left|1.9-\frac{S}{20}\right| = t+C_1.
\end{align*}

Solving the above for \emph{S} yields

\begin{align*}
-20 \ln\left|1.9-\frac{S}{20}\right| &= t+C_1 \\
\ln\left|1.9-\frac{S}{20}\right| &= -\frac{t}{20}-\frac{C_1}{20} \\
\left|1.9-\frac{S}{20}\right| &= e^{-\frac{t}{20}-\frac{C_1}{20}} \\
1.9-\frac{S}{20} &= \pm e^{-\frac{C_1}{20}} e^{-\frac{t}{20}}\\
S &= 20\left(1.9-C_2 e^{-t/20}\right), 
\end{align*}

with a different constant $C_2 = \pm e^{-C_1/20}$. Now we use the
initial condition \emph{S(0) = 0} to solve for
\emph{C\textsubscript{2}}:

\begin{align*}
0 = 20\left(1.9-C_2 e^{0}\right) = 20(1.9-C_2),
\end{align*}

hence \emph{C\textsubscript{2} = 1.9} and therefore the final answer is

\begin{align*}
S(t) = 20\left(1.9-1.9e^{-t/20}\right).
\end{align*}
